Name: Lankford, James
text:
Today I voted to support a Continuing Resolution to keep the government operating. This provides certainty for our military, veterans, law enforcement, border personnel, and others who rely on the continuity of essential services. However, we cannot continue down this path. This marks yet another year in which we are voting on stopgap measures rather than doing the serious work of passing appropriations bills.
¬†
Majority Leader Schumer has not brought a single appropriations bill to the Senate floor. This failure is deeply concerning. Our national debt continues to grow, and runaway spending remains unchecked because we aren‚Äôt taking the time to engage in real debate over how to responsibly manage taxpayer dollars.
¬†
While avoiding a government shutdown is critical, it is equally important that we do the hard work of governing. Congress must get back to passing individual appropriations bills to address both the immediate needs of the nation and plan for the future.¬†Kicking the can down the road is not a plan‚Äîit‚Äôs just hoping nobody notices the mess. Oklahomans deserve better than the uncertainty of last-minute CRs, and I will continue to push for regular order in the Senate.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1960, the first televised debate between major party presidential candidates took place in U.S. history. 

Democratic Senator John F. Kennedy and Republican Vice President Richard Nixon debated U.S. domestic issues in a Chicago studio. Kennedy recognized that the debates could significantly boost his campaign. The 43-year-old Massachusetts senator, who had risen from relative obscurity to become the Democratic nominee, faced challenges regarding his perceived inexperience as a leader. In preparation, he reviewed key facts and napped and tanned before the debate. He appeared well-rested and fit, a fact later acknowledged by Richard Nixon.

In contrast, Nixon was exhausted and unwell. The sitting Vice President had been campaigning vigorously across all 50 states and had recently spent time in the hospital due to a knee injury and subsequent infection. Arriving at the debate with a fever and in pain, he looked haggard, with debate producer Don Hewitt remarking that he appeared "like death warmed over." Despite his condition, Nixon chose to proceed with the debate, fearing that withdrawing would make him seem cowardly.

Interestingly, listeners on the radio believed Nixon won the presidential debate, while viewers who watched it thought Kennedy was the victor.

Although Nixon performed better in the second and third debates, Kennedy ultimately won the election, securing 49.7% of the popular vote against Nixon's 49.6%, making it one of the closest elections in U.S. history.

Nixon returned to presidential politics in 1968 but chose not to debate his opponent, similar to Lyndon Johnson in 1964. Televised debates resumed in 1976 and have been a staple of presidential campaigns ever since.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Monica T. Davis, a native of Wilson County, is the executive director of Preservation of Wilson. She is passionate about historic preservation, architectural history, and design. 

Her commitment to the community intensified after witnessing the demolition of historic shotgun homes in east Wilson, prompting her to form R.O.C.K. Her non-profit organization aims to preserve these irreplaceable structures. By transforming historic buildings into affordable housing solutions, Monica ensures community members can reside in homes that honor their rich heritage.

Monica channels her expertise into her hometown, fostering a deep sense of pride and connection among residents. She is preserving history and igniting hope for a vibrant future.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This week, our Hometown Hero spotlight shines on a man whose remarkable career embodies dedication, leadership, and an unyielding commitment to the safety and well-being of our community. As we celebrate his retirement, we honor his legacy of nearly four decades of service and leadership. Meet Chief Dean Logan, this week's Hometown Hero.

For 37 years, Chief Dean Logan has been a cornerstone of strength, compassion, and leadership, shaping the @DoylestownTwp Police Department and the very spirit of our community. From his first day on the job in 1987, Chief Logan embodied what it means to serve‚Äîalways ready to roll up his sleeves, face challenges head-on, and rise to the occasion whenever Doylestown needed him. His rise from patrol officer to detective and ultimately to Chief reflects his remarkable talents, unparalleled character and integrity, and commitment to excellence.

Over the past twelve years as Chief, his visionary leadership has transformed the Doylestown Police Department. He not only grew the department in size; he elevated its stature. By embracing cutting-edge technology, strengthening community relations, and leading the charge to secure accreditation with the Pennsylvania Law Enforcement Accreditation Program‚Äîan honor held by fewer than 10% of departments statewide‚ÄîChief Logan set a new standard of excellence. His tireless efforts have made Doylestown a safer, brighter, more resilient community. 

What makes Chief Logan exceptional is not just his professional accomplishments‚Äîbut his heart and ability to lead with kindness, strength, and respect, both within his department and throughout the community he proudly calls home. A Doylestown native and Central Bucks East graduate, Chief Logan returned home after attending Shippensburg University, driven by a deep desire to give back to the community that shaped him.

Barbara Lyons, the longtime Township Supervisor, said it best: "Chief Logan did not just lead by example but built a department that reflects his values. The officers who serve under him do not just show up to hand out speeding tickets‚Äîthey are a part of the fabric of this community. That is Chief's legacy."

Please join me in honoring Chief Logan for a lifetime of extraordinary leadership and service‚Äîa true Hometown Hero who gave his all to make our community safer, stronger, and more united. While he will be missed, we celebrate this well-earned milestone and extend our heartfelt congratulations as he embarks on a well-deserved retirement. Chief Logan‚Äôs impact on Doylestown is immeasurable, and his legacy will inspire future generations of leaders. Thank you, Chief Logan, and congratulations!

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
It was incredible to be present at a ceremony to witness the United States military‚Äôs historic apology for the devastating 1869 bombardment of Kake. I have heard for many years how the people of Kake have not been able to heal from the trauma of the Navy‚Äôs attack. Families have shared the stories of the destruction, which led to deaths among children and elders. These families have had to live with that sadness and unresolved trauma for too long. One of the cultural values the people of Kake carry is spiritual and cultural balance. When trying to find that balance, apologies need to be made, to say ‚ÄòI am sorry, we failed you.‚Äô 

While far overdue, it is appropriate now that our military offered this apology to the people of Kake for their loss. I commend the clan leaders in Kake for their humble acceptance of the Navy‚Äôs apology, and hope that this acknowledgment will promote healing from the intergenerational trauma caused by the United States government‚Äôs mistakes. It was my great honor to have worked alongside the community of Kake to advocate for this historic event.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1964, the Warren Commission, tasked with investigating the assassination of President Kennedy by Lee Harvey Oswald, releases a report, concluding that Oswald acted as a "lone gunman.‚Äù

President Kennedy was shot and killed while traveling in an open-top limousine during a motorcade in Dallas in 1963.

Less than an hour after the shooting, Lee Harvey Oswald, a former Marine employed at the Texas School Book Depository, shot a police officer who questioned him. He was arrested in a movie theater shortly after. Oswald was charged with the murders of Kennedy and Officer J.D. Tippit.

The following day, as Oswald was being transferred from the Dallas police headquarters, Jack Ruby shot him with a concealed revolver in front of police and reporters. Ruby, a nightclub owner with ties to organized crime, claimed he acted out of anger over Kennedy‚Äôs assassination.

As Oswald was killed shortly after assassinating Kennedy, his motive remained unclear. In response, President Johnson established the Warren Commission to investigate the assassination. Led by Chief Justice Earl Warren, the commission included U.S. senators, representatives, a former CIA director, and a former World Bank president.

Over nearly a year, the commission examined reports from the FBI, Secret Service, and others, reviewed Oswald‚Äôs background, and interviewed hundreds of witnesses while visiting the assassination site in Dallas. 

The commission released an 888-page report concluding that Oswald fired three shots from a sixth-floor window of the Texas School Book Depository, killing Kennedy and injuring Governor Connally. While the report detailed Oswald‚Äôs life and connections, it did not explore his motives. It also criticized the Secret Service for inadequate security during Kennedy‚Äôs Dallas visit and stated that Jack Ruby acted alone in killing Oswald.

This finding did not satisfy many witnesses and researchers who found inconsistencies in the report. Various conspiracy theories emerged, implicating entities like the Cuban and Soviet governments, organized crime, the FBI, CIA, and even Vice President Johnson. Critics pointed to ballistics evidence and a home movie that seemed to challenge the claim that three bullets from Oswald caused Kennedy's fatal wounds and Connally's injuries.

In the late 1970s, the House Select Committee on Assassinations (HSCA) conducted a new investigation. Their report supported the Warren Commission's finding that Oswald fired two bullets but also suggested a high probability of a second gunman and an unspecified conspiracy behind the assassination. Both reports remain subjects of debate.

The extensive documentation from the Warren Commission is housed in the National Archives, with much available to the public; however, access to Kennedy‚Äôs autopsy records is highly restricted, requiring special permission or affiliation with a presidential or congressional commission.

Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
‚ÄúThe world must know what happened and never forget.‚Äù
~General Dwight D. Eisenhower 

Yesterday, I presented a flag flown over the U.S. Capitol to Cold Spring Harbor High School at The Remembrance Project game during Cold Spring Harbor HS‚Äôs homecoming.

During WWII, in the late fall of 1944, with Paris secure and ultimate victory inevitable, a football game was organized for Christmas Day. The 101st Airborne Division paratroopers, who had already seen hard fighting in Normandy and the Netherlands, planned what they named the Champagne Bowl. The big game was set to take place on December 25, 1944. When the Battle of the Bulge broke out, the soldiers had to drop everything and march to the Ardennes, abandoning what would become known as The Game That Never Happened.

These ‚ÄúRemembrance‚Äù games serve to remind us of those young soldiers that never had a chance to play their game, and instead went off to one of the deadliest campaigns of WWII.

This morning, we came together at the Middletown Grange Fairgrounds for the deeply moving ribbon-cutting of Wesley‚Äôs Playground‚Äîa heartfelt tribute to 5-year-old Wesley Roche, the beloved son of Nicole and Alex Roche of Richboro. Wesley‚Äôs spirit touched all who knew him, and though his time with us was far too short, he filled this world with an unforgettable light before cancer took him from us.

As Co-Chair of the Congressional Cancer Caucus, I remain deeply committed to fighting for the funding, research, and innovation needed to end cancer once and for all.

To Nicole, Alex, and the entire Roche family‚Äîyour love and resilience have created a lasting legacy for Wesley, one that will inspire and uplift our community for generations. Today, we honored Wesley not in sadness, but in the enduring light he left behind‚Äîa light that will continue to shine brightly through every child who finds joy at Wesley‚Äôs Playground.

Name: LaHood, Darin
text:
The world is a much better place without Hezbollah Secretary General Hassan Nasrallah. I commend the effort to eliminate Nasrallah, who has the blood of countless innocent civilians on his hands, and the United States should stand with our allies in the face of terrorist threats.¬†

For years, Nasrallah and Hezbollah, an Iranian terrorist proxy, have sought to sow divide in Lebanon and the Middle East, disrupting ongoing efforts for peace in the region. In the years since the Beirut port blast, Hezbollah has obstructed the democratic process in Lebanon, prevented the formation of a government and election of an independent president, and blocked humanitarian assistance to the Lebanese people. Hezbollah's proxy bidding for Tehran has decimated the Lebanese economy, propped up corruption, and prevented the people of Lebanon from exercising their right to sovereignty, stability, and democracy.¬†

Like many Lebanese Americans, both in my district and across the country, I share concern for the people of Lebanon and pray for their continued safety. The death and destruction in Lebanon falls squarely on the shoulders of Nasrallah, Hezbollah, and their backers in Iran. Hezbollah's influence in Lebanon must be extinguished to allow for a prosperous future of the Lebanese people. The United States¬†must continue to support the Lebanese Armed Forces (LAF) to keep stability in the country and efforts to quickly open Parliament and allow the Lebanese to elect an independent president that will support the needs of the Lebanese people.¬†

I stand ready to work with the Administration, my colleagues in Congress, and the Lebanese diaspora community in America to support the work of a secure, independent and peaceful future for the Lebanese people.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Congratulations to Aidan Johnston of Troop 316 for earning the distinguished rank of Eagle Scout‚Äîan achievement that marks him as a leader of character, vision, and unwavering dedication to service.
 
For his Eagle Scout project, Aidan led a dedicated team in refurbishing the brick pathway at Historic Summerseat in Morrisville‚Äîan iconic site that served as General George Washington‚Äôs headquarters in December 1776. Summerseat was also home to two of our nation‚Äôs founding fathers, George Clymer and Robert Morris, both signers of the Declaration of Independence and the U.S. Constitution. Aidan‚Äôs connection to this project runs deep, as he is a direct descendant of Robert Morris, for whom the town of Morrisville is named, making this initiative even more meaningful.
 
Please join me in celebrating Aidan for his exceptional achievement and wishing him continued success!

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1982, the Tylenol scare began when seven Chicago residents died over the course of a few days after taking cyanide-laced extra-strength Tylenol capsules. 

After initial investigations of the deaths of the victims, doctors determined cyanide contamination, leading Johnson & Johnson to issue a historic recall of 31 million bottles. The cyanide had not originated in the company's facilities; rather, someone had likely tampered with the bottles after purchasing them.

Police used bullhorns throughout the streets of Chicago to urge residents to dispose of any Tylenol in their homes. Public health officials distributed flyers, and stores removed all Tylenol products from their shelves.

James Lewis, who claimed to be the Tylenol killer, sent a letter to Johnson & Johnson demanding $1 million to stop the poisonings. However, after an extensive investigation, authorities found no connection between him and the Chicago incidents. He was charged with extortion and sentenced to 20 years in prison but was released in 1995 after serving 13 years.

In response to the crisis, Tylenol introduced tamper-evident seals and solid pills, making contamination more difficult. The ‚ÄúTylenol bill‚Äù passed in 1983 made tampering with consumer products a federal offense. Johnson & Johnson's handling of the situation is considered a model for crisis management, and their stock rebounded within two months of the scare.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson calls for the Censure of Rep. Clay Higgins after Racist remarks against Haitians

Louisiana and Haiti have a shared history. Today, we should be celebrating and reflecting upon the rich and intertwined heritage of these connected cultures. These two regions, though separated by the Gulf of Mexico, share a bond that has profoundly shaped their cultures, economies, and identities.

In 1791, enslaved Africans in Haiti rose against their oppressors, leading to the first successful slave rebellion in history. This revolution culminated in Haiti becoming the first independent Black republic in 1804.
The impact of this Revolution extended far beyond the island‚Äôs shores. France, weakened by the loss of its most profitable colony sold the vast Louisiana Territory to the United States in 1803. This acquisition doubled the size of America and opened up the continent for westward expansion. There would be no America as we know it, without Haiti.

The connections between Haiti and Louisiana are deeply cultural. Following the Revolution, many refugees, including free people of color, planters, and enslaved individuals, fled to Louisiana, particularly New Orleans. They brought with them their customs, cuisine, music, and religious practices, which have since become integral to the cultural fabric of Louisiana. The word ‚ÄúGumbo‚Äù itself comes from the West African word ‚Äúki ngombo,‚Äù which translates to okra.

The influence of Haitian culture is evident in the vibrant Creole cuisine, the rhythms of jazz, and the spiritual practices of Voodoo. The architecture of the French Quarter bears the mark of this shared heritage and Creole languages reflect their common roots in French colonialism and African heritage.

This shared history is what makes the words of Louisiana Congressman Clay Higgins all the more disgusting, abhorrent, and despicable. Congressman Higgins posted on his official account:

"LOL, These Haitians are wild. Eating pets, vudu, nastiest country in the western hemisphere, cults, slapstick gangsters... but damned if they don‚Äôt feel all sophisticated now, filing charges against our President and VP, All these thugs better get their mind right and their ass out of our country before January 20th‚Äù

These comments represent a new low even for Extreme MAGA Republicans. Higgins, a former policeman and sheriff's deputy in St. Landry Parish was disciplined by his commanding officer in Opelousas after he struck a handcuffed Black man and then lied about it amid an internal probe. He has bragged about voting for and supporting Klansman David Duke. In 2020, when protesters marched to bring justice for Breonna Taylor he used his official House account to post:

‚ÄúIf this shows up, we‚Äôll consider the armed presence a real threat,‚Äù "I'd drop any 10 of you where you stand," "Nothing personal. We just eliminate the threat. We don't care what color you are. We don't care if you're left or right. if you show up like this, if We recognize a threat...you won't walk away."

What‚Äôs worse, is not the sentiments of Mr. Higgins but the response from his fellow Republicans. As Martin Luther King, Jr. once said ‚ÄúHistory will have to record that the greatest tragedy of this period of social transition was not the strident clamor of the bad people, but the appalling silence of the good people.‚Äù Mr. Higgins holds deep-seated fears and hatred of people who do not look like him. But the silence of Republican leadership has been so much more deafening and hurtful.

I call on Speaker of the House Johnson and the leaders of the Republican Party to join us in condemning Congressman Higgins; additionally, I join my colleagues in the Congressional Black Caucus in calling for the censure of the Member. His statements violate the House Rules regarding the conduct of a member and put the lives of millions of Haitians, other immigrants, and people of color in danger.

Speaker Johnson has said that Mr. Higgins has prayed on the issues and has atoned for his statement saying ‚ÄúI‚Äôm sure he probably regrets some of the language he used. But you know, we move forward. We believe in redemption around here.‚Äù However, Mr. Higgins has shown no such remorse saying:

¬∑ ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs all true!‚Äù
¬∑ ‚ÄúI can put up another controversial post tomorrow if you want me to. I mean, we do have freedom of speech. I‚Äôll say what I want.‚Äù
¬∑ ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not a big deal to me. It‚Äôs like something stuck to the bottom of my boot. Just scrape it off and move on with my life.‚Äù

Mr. Higgins and his Project 2025, Extreme MAGA Republican allies are intent on doubling down and tripling down of hateful rhetoric and division. For this reason, the House of Representatives must act with one voice and vote to censure Representative Higgins.

@CBCInstitute @CongresswomanSC @HaitianBridge @HaitiInfoProj @HACSONET @hayonlinenews

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Today, we remember #DikembeMutombo, a giant both on and off the basketball court.

Born on June 25, 1966, in Kinshasa, #Zaire, Mutombo was one of ten children. His father, an educator, ensured that his children had access to good schools. Dikembe‚Äôs early dreams were of becoming a doctor, and he eventually mastered nine languages, including French, English, Spanish, Portuguese, and five Central African dialects.

His journey from #Kinshasa to the NBA is a testament to his determination and resilience.  Mutombo was a four-time NBA Defensive Player of the Year and an eight-time All-Star. His iconic finger wag and relentless defense made him a household name, but it was his humanitarian efforts that truly defined his legacy.

He dedicated his life to improving health and education in his native Democratic Republic of #Congo. Through the Dikembe Mutombo Foundation, he built the Biamba Marie Mutombo Hospital, providing critical healthcare services to thousands. His initiatives included free cervical and breast cancer screenings, knee and cataract surgeries.

As a UNICEF global ambassador and a tireless advocate, Dikembe‚Äôs impact was felt worldwide. His work with the NBA Cares program and various international relief agencies showcased his unwavering commitment to making the world a better place.

Rest in peace, @officialmutombo  Your impact will be felt for generations to come.  #RIPDikembe #Legend #Humanitarian #NBA #NotInMyHouse #MountMutombo  #DRC #DemocraticRepublicOfCongo

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This weekend, I had the great honor of joining the @TMFoundation in paying tribute to three of the greatest heroes PA-1 has ever known. We began by honoring Ensign Sarah Joy Mitchell, a Neshaminy High School graduate, who gave her life in service to our nation at just 23. Then, at the 9/11 Heroes Run in Doylestown, we stood united in memory of 1st Lt. Colby Umbrell, a Central Bucks East High School graduate, who made the ultimate defending our freedom during Operation Iraqi Freedom, and CAPT. Connor Bednarzyk, of Doylestown, who gave his life in service to our nation during a training mission in 2018.

These three heroes represent the very best of our community and the highest ideals of our nation. Their legacies remind us that freedom comes at a cost, and we owe them‚Äîand all who have served and sacrificed‚Äîa debt that can never be repaid.

To Ryan Manion and the incredible TMF team, thank you for your steadfast commitment to supporting our veterans and preserving these legacies. It has been an honor to work alongside you over the years to champion veteran initiatives‚ÄîI am grateful for your friendship, leadership, and relentless dedication to our nation‚Äôs heroes.

‚ñ™Ô∏è Repeals the Bank Secrecy Act‚Äôs SAR and CTR reporting requirements while maintaining record-keeping provisions.

Name: Scott, Rick
text: Since Category 4 Hurricane Helene made its devastating landfall in the Big Bend and caused massive and destructive storm surge along hundreds of miles of Florida‚Äôs Gulf Coast, I have been traveling to impacted communities to survey damage and coordinate resources between the local, state and federal governments. What I have seen, from the catastrophic damage in Cedar Key, to the massive destruction caused by unprecedented storm surge in communities from Fort Myers Beach to Siesta Key and Anna Maria Island and north to Pinellas, Pasco and Hernando counties is heartbreaking. News reports of the devastation in Georgia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and other communities impacted by Hurricane Helene are also devastating. Floridians are resilient, but the response and recovery from this storm demands the full and immediate support of government at every level to get families and businesses back to normal. While I know from my experience with previous hurricanes that @FEMA and @SBAgov damage assessments take time, I am today urging Majority Leader @SenSchumer to immediately reconvene the U.S. Senate when those assessments are completed so that we can pass the clean supplemental disaster funding bill and other disaster relief legislation, like my¬†Federal Disaster Tax Relief Act,¬†needed to ensure the full recovery of families in all impacted communities. While we wait for this critical information, I¬†will keep fighting to make sure that FEMA, the SBA, and the entire federal government is working in total collaboration with state and local officials so we continue to get resources and aid deployed quickly.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1890, Yosemite National Park is established. 

Renowned for its natural wonders like Half Dome and giant sequoias, this achievement was largely driven by environmental advocate John Muir and others, with support from President Benjamin Harrison. 

The park's creation followed a history of Native American habitation disrupted by the 1849 gold rush, which led to ecological damage and increased tourism. President Abraham Lincoln designated Yosemite Valley and the Mariposa Grove as a public trust to protect them from exploitation, laying the groundwork for future national parks.

Muir and fellow advocate Robert Underwood Johnson pushed for national park status to protect the meadows around Yosemite from overgrazing by sheep. Their efforts resulted in the designation of over 1,500 square miles as Yosemite National Park, the third national park in the U.S. Federal jurisdiction eventually extended to Yosemite Valley and Mariposa Grove. Ansel Adams later captured the park's beauty through iconic black-and-white photographs. 

Today, Yosemite attracts over 3 million visitors each year, who come to explore its breathtaking features, including Yosemite Falls, Half Dome, El Capitan, and the giant sequoia groves.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This weekend, Bristol Borough brought history to life as the community gathered to celebrate the 200th anniversary of Marquis de Lafayette‚Äôs legendary 1824 Farewell Tour‚Äîa tribute that truly captured the heart and spirit of this special town.

The celebration featured a grand parade down Radcliffe Street, with local students passing out flowers, the Free Masons, Bristol Boro Police & Fire Companies, and the internationally renowned @Pennsbury_SD Marching Band leading the way. The event culminated in the unveiling of a new Lafayette Street marker and mural dedication, set to the beats of the Bristol High School Drum Line and debut performance of the Snyder-Girotti Elementary School Band. Adding to the historic significance was the display of the original ‚ÄúWelcome Friend‚Äù sign‚Äîfirst shown to greet Lafayette himself in 1824‚Äîa gesture of warmth and hospitality that has since become an enduring symbol of the Borough.

A special thank you to the incomparable Mary Gesualdi and the Bristol Cultural and Historical Foundation for your tireless efforts in bringing this extraordinary event to life and your continued dedication to preserving and honoring the rich history of Bristol Borough.

Name: Timmons, William R.
text:
An important update from Greenville County on debris pick up, medical shelter, food and water distribution, and the State Forester's Burning Ban for Greenville County:
---
For those in Greenville County needing critical assistance, please call 864-467-3428 between 7 a.m. and 7 p.m.

Greenville County will begin roadside disaster-generated debris pick up starting on Wednesday. Citizens in the unincorporated areas of the County can carefully place downed trees along their roads. Crews will get to everyone, so please be patient.

A medical shelter is open at the Bon Secours Wellness Arena for those who have electricity-dependent medical needs. Caregivers are welcome as well.

Bottle water and ready to eat meals are being distributed at 35 E. Antrim Drive at McAllister Square. The distribution site will be available 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.

The South Carolina Forestry Commission will issue a State Forester's Burning Ban for Greenville County, effective at 6 a.m. Tuesday, Oct. 1. The burning ban is intended to ease the strain on firefighting personnel and law enforcement officials ‚Äì from both the Forestry Commission and from local fire departments ‚Äì many of whom were dispatched to affected areas to assist with road clearing, damage assessment and related cleanup.

Greenville County Administration and Offices will open Tuesday, Oct. 1 at noon. You can make payments online, and during this time, credit card fees will be waived.

BREAKING: Rep. Luna Co-Sponsors Bipartisan Legislation Authorizing Additional FEMA Funding Amid Hurricane Helene Disaster

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

ST. PETERSBURG, FL‚ÄîToday, Congresswoman Anna Paulina Luna (R, FL-13) co-sponsored bipartisan legislation to support recovery efforts following Hurricane Helene‚Äôs devastating impact on Florida and other states across the nation. The bill, introduced by Congressman Jared Moskowitz (D, FL-23), allocates an additional $15 billion in response to Hurricane Helene, including $10 billion for the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) for disaster relief and emergency assistance and $5 billion in supplemental funding to the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) through the Community Development Block Grant Disaster Recovery (CDBG-DR) program.

‚ÄúMy constituents in Pinellas County depend on Congress to take swift and decisive action in the wake of this unprecedented disaster caused by Hurricane Helene,‚Äù said Congresswoman Luna. ‚ÄúI am ready and willing to return to Washington and ensure our communities receive the critical resources necessary for a rapid recovery. Americans are counting on us, and we must take immediate action to address their life-saving needs.‚Äù

The world is watching as Israeli families seek safety and shelter as waves of missile attacks light up the sky. The world is watching as Israeli families seek safety and shelter as waves of missile attacks light up the sky. We pray for their safety and urge the Biden-Harris Administration to deliver a strong message to the Iranian regime that this unjustified violence and terror must end. The strategy of appeasement has failed, and a policy of interdiction is not enough.
¬†
American leadership has never been more important, and the world should know that the United States will continue to stand firmly with Israel as it fights for its very survival. Our adversaries are carrying out increasingly dangerous attacks because of Biden and Harris' weak and failed foreign policy. The world needs America to return to a maximum pressure campaign against Iran, and President Biden needs to make clear that there will be decisive economic and potential military ramifications for these actions.
